# turboquant-serve

**KV-cache memory compression for any HuggingFace model. Drop-in replacement for `DynamicCache`. No fine-tuning. No calibration data. No kernel changes.**

Implements [TurboQuant (ICLR 2026)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.19874): random orthogonal rotation + Lloyd-Max scalar quantization applied to the KV cache at inference time.

---

## What this is

At long contexts, the KV cache becomes the bottleneck — not weights. TurboQuant compresses it 3–4× in Python, letting you run longer contexts on consumer GPUs without OOM.

**What you get:**
- 3–4× reduction in KV cache memory (tested: Gemma 4 E4B, RTX 4060 8GB)
- Same output quality for models ≥ 7B at 4-bit keys + 4-bit values
- Works with any HuggingFace model using standard `DynamicCache`
- OpenAI-compatible inference server with usage stats and TPS tracking

**What you don't get:**
- Faster token generation — dequantization happens in Python/PyTorch before attention, so there is no FLOP reduction. Speed is approximately the same as baseline for short contexts, and slightly better at very long contexts where you'd otherwise be memory-bandwidth bound.
- Magic compatibility — very small models (≤ 1B) or models with `head_dim=64` need 8-bit keys to maintain quality.

> **Note on QJL:** The paper describes Lloyd-Max + 1-bit QJL residual. This implementation uses Lloyd-Max only (MSE). Multiple independent community implementations found QJL *hurts* attention quality — softmax amplifies its variance. See the architecture section below.

---

## Results (Gemma 4 E4B, RTX 4060 Laptop 8GB)

```
tq-compare --model ./models/gemma4-e4b-4bit --prompt "Explain the Riemann hypothesis"
```

| Config | KV store | vs bf16 | Quality |
|--------|----------|---------|---------|
| Baseline bf16 | 1.6 MB (256 tok) | 1.0× | — |
| TQ 4-bit K + 4-bit V | 0.5 MB | **3.53×** | identical answer |
| TQ 4-bit K + 2-bit V | 0.3 MB | **5.29×** | identical answer |

At 32K context: baseline OOMs on 8GB VRAM. TQ 4-bit fits with ~2 GB headroom.

