## Architecture

```
TurboQuantCache (subclass of DynamicCache)
│
├── update(k, v, layer_idx)          ← called by transformers on every forward pass
│   ├── rotate: k, v = k @ R, v @ R  ← random orthogonal matrix, seeded by head_dim
│   ├── keys:   normalize → Lloyd-Max encode → bit-pack → store uint8
│   ├── values: group min/max quant  → bit-pack → store uint8
│   └── return _decode()             ← dequantized k, v for attention
│
└── _decode(layer_idx)
    ├── unpack + Lloyd-Max decode → restore magnitude → k @ R.T
    └── group dequantize → v @ R.T
```

**Rotation:** A fixed random orthogonal matrix spreads energy evenly across dimensions before quantization, reducing worst-case quantization error significantly vs. quantizing raw activations.

**Keys vs values:** Keys are normalized to the unit sphere then Lloyd-Max quantized (MSE-optimal for the Beta distribution prior). Values are group-quantized with affine scaling (min/max per group of 32).

**Why no QJL:** QJL provides unbiased inner product estimates but introduces variance. Softmax in attention amplifies this variance exponentially. MSE-only quantization has lower variance and consistently achieves better end-task quality. Confirmed by multiple independent implementations.

---

## Bit config guide

| Model size | Recommended | Notes |
|------------|-------------|-------|
| ≥ 13B | `--key-bits 4 --value-bits 4` | Full quality at 3.5× |
| 7B–13B | `--key-bits 4 --value-bits 4` | Tested, works well |
| 1B–7B | `--key-bits 8 --value-bits 4` | head_dim=64 needs 8-bit keys |
| < 1B | Not recommended | Tiny models have no redundancy to absorb compression loss |

---

## Roadmap

- [ ] Triton fused dequant+attention kernel — compute attention on quantized K/V without materializing bf16 (true FLOP + bandwidth reduction)
- [ ] Residual window — keep last N tokens in fp16 for recency quality
- [ ] Outlier-aware mixed precision — more bits for outlier channels
- [ ] vLLM integration
- [ ] Multi-GPU / tensor parallel support

